==History== The Mount is said to have been built in 1797<ref name="gov.uk"/> but one of it first residents was Captain [[Harry Harmwood]] who was a [[Naval Commissioner]] in Gibraltar from 1793 to 1794. The Mount was purchased in 1799 and for over two hundred years it was the home of the most senior naval officer in Gibraltar.<ref name=musteen>{{cite book|last=Musteen|first=Jason R.|title=Nelson's Refuge: Gibraltar in the Age of Napoleon|year=2011|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1591145455|page=402|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HThZ_inxa14C&dq=%22the+mount%22+gibraltar+navy&source=gbs_navlinks_s|accessdate=29 November 2012}}</ref> It was part of the military presence here even before the massive extension of the naval facilities at the end of the nineteenth century when £1.5m was spent on work that included three dry docks and the [[Detached Mole, Gibraltar Harbour|Detached Mole]].<ref name=ff>{{cite book|last=Fa|first=Darren|title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945|year=2006|publisher=Osprey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&dq=mount+gibraltar&source=gbs_navlinks_s|author2=[[Clive Finlayson]] |page=40}}</ref> That work had originally been suggested in 1871 by Captain [[Augustus Phillimore]] who was the senior naval officer in Gibraltar and would have lived here.
[[File:Colonel William Willoughby Verner, Sanger Shepherd process, by Sarah Acland 1903.png|thumb|left|Colonel [[William Willoughby Cole Verner]] at The Mount, Sanger-Shepherd process, by [[Sarah Angelina Acland]], 1903.]] In 1903 it was home to early use of colour photography. In 1903 [[Sarah Angelina Acland]] visited her brother [[Sir William Acland, 2nd Baronet|Admiral Sir William Acland]] in Gibraltar. She was said to be earliest traveller to use colour photography. Acland took photographs of [[Europa Point]] looking out from Europe to Africa, pictures of flora in the Admiral's residence, ''The Mount'' and a photo of the local ornithologist Colonel [[William Willoughby Cole Verner]]. He would have had to keep still for two minutes whilst three different pictures were taken to capture the red, blue and green components of the image.<ref name=matters>{{cite web|title=news release "Sarah Angelina Acland re-discovered as one of the pioneers of colour photography"|url=http://mattersphotographical.wordpress.com/2012/11/14/sarah-angelina-acland-images/|publisher=mattersphotographical|accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref> In 1904 she exhibited in Britain 33 three-colour prints under the title ''The Home of the Osprey, Gibraltar''.<ref name=exhibit>{{cite web|title=1904 Forty-ninth Annual Exhibition of the Royal Photographic Society of Great Britain|url=http://erps.dmu.ac.uk/exhibit_details.php?serial=23726|publisher=De Montfort University|accessdate=24 February 2013}}</ref>
Currently ''The Mount'' is owned by the [[Government of Gibraltar]]. It is used as a wedding venue.<ref name="gov.uk"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wedgibraltar.com/info2.cfm?info_id=47753 | title=GETTING WED AT GIBRALTAR’S REGISTRY OFFICE | author=WedGibraltar}}</ref>
